# Trivy waivers — neo4j image only (wired to the neo4j scan step in
# .github/workflows/ci.yml via the `trivyignores:` input; NOT applied to the
# pgvector or ollama scans, which stay strict).
#
# Context (Issue #2): the neo4j base image is pinned to
# neo4j:5.26.27-community-ubi10. Switching from the Debian (`-trixie`) base to
# Red Hat UBI-10 already eliminated all 14 HIGH/CRITICAL OS-package CVEs
# (including 2 CRITICAL gnutls) — those are NOT waived, they are fixed by the
# base choice. What remains are CVEs in jars Neo4j bundles itself: 4 HIGH in
# netty (4.1.135.Final), 1 HIGH in jetty (12.1.8), 1 HIGH in jackson-core
# (2.21.1 + 2.21.3), 1 HIGH in the bundled Apache Shiro auth framework
# (shiro-core 2.1.0), and 2 HIGH in the bundled Jackson databind
# (jackson-databind 2.21.1 / 2.21.3). They are identical across every base
# variant and cannot be fixed without a new Neo4j release that bumps the
# bundled jars (netty >= 4.1.136.Final; jetty >= 12.1.10; jackson-core >= 2.21.4;
# shiro-core >= 2.2.1; jackson-databind >= 2.21.4).
#
# 2026-07-23 — the 5.26.25 -> 5.26.27 bump moved netty 4.1.132 -> 4.1.135, which
# FIXED the six netty CVEs previously waived here (CVE-2026-42583/42584/42587,
# CVE-2026-44249/45416/50010). Their waivers were deleted rather than carried —
# a fix always beats an ignore. The netty entries that remain below are a
# *different*, newer wave (published 2026-07-21/22) that 4.1.135 does not fix.
#
# Why these are acceptable for THIS deployment (spec §6.7 accept-with-justification):
#   - Story Forge runs Neo4j bound to 127.0.0.1 only, single trusted user,
#     non-root container, no-new-privileges. There is no untrusted network peer.
#   - None of them is RCE, and none discloses data. Most are denial-of-service
#     (resource exhaustion: unbounded allocation, decompression amplification, a
#     memory leak, an event-loop hang). Two are authentication/authorization
#     bypasses — Jetty Digest auth (CVE-2026-10050) and Shiro's LDAP realm
#     (CVE-2026-49268) — but both sit in authentication mechanisms this
#     deployment does not enable: Neo4j Community uses its own native auth realm,
#     with no Digest authenticator and no LDAP (Enterprise-only). Two are
#     deserialization-allowlist bypasses (CVE-2026-54512/54513) that require
#     attacker-controlled JSON, which never reaches Neo4j here.
#   - Every one of them requires an untrusted network peer or untrusted input
#     that this single-user, 127.0.0.1-bound deployment never has: the only
#     client is the Story Forge backend on the same host.
#   - Drop each entry the moment a Neo4j 5.26.x patch ships bundling the fixed
#     jar version named in its justification; a re-scan should then pass clean.
#     This has already paid out once — see the 2026-07-23 note above, where a
#     tag bump retired six netty waivers outright.
#
# All waivers across images are also indexed in infra/trivy/WAIVERS.md (the
# review register: fixed-in versions + drop conditions, checked periodically).
#
# Revisit: each Neo4j patch bump (next time the image tag is updated).

# ── Bundled netty jars — wave published 2026-07-21/22, added 2026-07-23 ──
# All four are fixed in netty 4.1.136.Final (4.2.16.Final on the 4.2.x line);
# neo4j 5.26.27 bundles 4.1.135.Final and even 5.26.28 (2026-07-22) has not caught
# up, so no released tag fixes them yet.
# Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles netty >= 4.1.136.Final
# (re-scan to confirm all four are gone); checked at each neo4j tag bump.

# CVE-2026-59901 — netty-codec (Bzip2Decoder): a malformed bzip2 stream traps the
# run-length-encoding state machine in Bzip2BlockDecompressor.read() in an infinite
# loop, permanently hanging the event-loop thread (DoS). NOT REACHABLE: reaching
# Bzip2Decoder requires a bzip2-compressed stream through a netty pipeline that
# installs the compression codec. Neo4j serves Bolt (7687) and HTTP (7474); neither
# negotiates bzip2, so the handler is never in the pipeline — and both are bound to
# 127.0.0.1 with a single trusted local client. (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB,
# GHSA-558v-64gr-wgg4.)
CVE-2026-59901

# CVE-2026-55831 — netty-codec-http (SPDY SETTINGS): a peer-declared SETTINGS entry
# count is materialized into a TreeMap without a count cap, so one ~2 MiB SETTINGS
# frame creates 262144 entries — network-input-to-heap amplification (DoS).
# CVE-2026-55833 — netty-codec-http (SPDY zlib header block): header inflation
# continues after maxHeaderSize is exceeded, so a 12 KiB compressed block forces
# a 12 MiB decode (compression-amplified DoS).
# CVE-2026-56745 — netty-codec-http (SpdyHttpDecoder): a pooled ByteBuf allocated for
# a SYN_STREAM is never released when the peer sends RST_STREAM, permanently leaking
# native memory (DoS).
# NOT REACHABLE — all three are in netty's **SPDY** codec. SPDY is a deprecated
# protocol (superseded by HTTP/2) that Neo4j does not implement or expose: no
# SpdyFrameCodec / SpdyHttpDecoder is ever installed in its pipeline, so the
# vulnerable code is unreachable regardless of input. Defence in depth: all three
# need an untrusted remote peer, and Neo4j is bound to 127.0.0.1 with a single
# trusted local client. (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB: GHSA-6jqx-86gh-f27w,
# GHSA-mvh2-crg5-v77c, GHSA-jppx-w49h-x2qq.)
CVE-2026-55831
CVE-2026-55833
CVE-2026-56745

# ── Bundled Eclipse Jetty (Neo4j's HTTP server stack) — added 2026-07-23 ──
# CVE-2026-10050 — jetty-security / jetty-ee8-security (12.1.8): Jetty's
# DigestAuthentication.apply() hashes credentials via getBytes(ISO_8859_1), which
# silently replaces every character above U+00FF with '?'. An attacker who knows a
# victim's username can then substitute '?' for each non-Latin-1 character in the
# password and produce an identical MD5 Digest response — an authentication bypass
# for passwords containing non-Latin-1 characters (CJK, Cyrillic, Arabic, emoji).
# NOT REACHABLE here: the flaw is in **HTTP Digest** authentication, which this
# deployment never uses. Neo4j Community authenticates via its own native realm
# (`NEO4J_AUTH` basic auth over a 127.0.0.1-bound listener); Jetty's Digest
# authenticator is not configured, and no outbound Digest client auth is performed.
# There is also no untrusted client to mount the substitution: single trusted local
# user, no LAN or public exposure.
# Fixed in jetty 12.1.10 (12.0.36 on the 12.0.x line); neo4j 5.26.27 and .28 both
# bundle 12.1.8. Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles
# jetty >= 12.1.10. (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB, GHSA-2fvj-hgj9-j2gr.)
CVE-2026-10050

# ── Bundled Jackson core (streaming JSON parser) — added 2026-07-23 ──
# GHSA-r7wm-3cxj-wff9 — com.fasterxml.jackson.core:jackson-core (2.21.1 and 2.21.3):
# the non-blocking/async parser's maxNumberLength guard can be bypassed by feeding
# digits across many small chunks, so an unbounded number token accumulates —
# a resource-exhaustion DoS. (An incomplete fix for GHSA-72hv-8253-57qq.)
# NOT REACHABLE here: it needs UNTRUSTED JSON fed to Jackson's async parser. Neo4j
# is bound to 127.0.0.1 with the Story Forge backend as its only client, and queries
# travel over Bolt (a binary protocol), not JSON. No attacker-controlled JSON reaches
# this parser. Resource exhaustion only — no data disclosure, no RCE.
# Fixed in jackson-core 2.21.4 (2.22.1 on the 2.22.x line); neo4j 5.26.27 bundles
# 2.21.1 + 2.21.3. Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles
# jackson-core >= 2.21.4. (Verified vs GitHub Advisory DB; the advisory has no CVE id.)
GHSA-r7wm-3cxj-wff9

# ── Bundled Apache Shiro (Neo4j's auth framework) — added 2026-06-19 ──
# CVE-2026-49268 — org.apache.shiro:shiro-core (shiro-core-2.1.0.jar): LDAP
# injection via insufficient escaping of RFC-2253 special characters when
# constructing a Distinguished Name (DN) in the DefaultLdapRealm class —
# potentially authentication bypass / user impersonation. Fixed in Shiro 2.2.1
# (also 3.0.0-alpha-2). (Verified vs the Apache Shiro security-reports page;
# the CVE is too fresh for NVD / the GitHub Advisory DB as of 2026-06-19.)
# NOT REACHABLE here: the flaw is in Shiro's *LDAP authentication realm*, but
# Neo4j LDAP/AD auth is an ENTERPRISE-only feature — this deployment runs Neo4j
# COMMUNITY (neo4j:5.26.x-community-ubi10) with only the native auth realm, so
# DefaultLdapRealm is never configured or instantiated; there is no LDAP
# directory and no DN is ever built from user input. Defence in depth: Neo4j is
# bound to 127.0.0.1, single trusted local user, native NEO4J_AUTH basic auth.
# Bundled by Neo4j like the netty jars above — neo4j 5.26.26 (and the unsoaked
# .27) still ship shiro-core 2.1.0 (verified by a local Trivy scan 2026-06-19),
# so no image bump fixes it yet.
# Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles shiro-core >= 2.2.1
# (re-scan to confirm CVE-2026-49268 is gone); checked at each neo4j tag bump.
CVE-2026-49268

# ── Bundled Jackson databind (Neo4j's JSON (de)serialization) — added 2026-06-24 ──
# A sibling pair (GHSA-j3rv-43j4-c7qm / GHSA pair), both HIGH, both published
# 2026-06-23, both fixed in jackson-databind 2.21.4 (also 2.18.8 on the 2.18.x line,
# 3.1.4 on the 3.x line). Trivy finds them in two bundled jars: jackson-databind-2.21.1.jar
# (2.21.1) and the jackson-databind copy shaded into parquet-jackson-1.17.0.jar (2.19.2) —
# both versions fall in the >= 2.19.0, <= 2.21.3 vulnerable range. (Verified vs GitHub
# Advisory DB: CVE-2026-54512 ranges 2.10.0-2.18.7 / 2.19.0-2.21.3 / 3.0.0-3.1.3.)
#
# CVE-2026-54512 — PolymorphicTypeValidator (PTV) bypass via generic type parameters:
# a crafted generic type can smuggle a subtype past the PTV allowlist, re-enabling unsafe
# polymorphic deserialization (the classic gadget-chain RCE class).
# CVE-2026-54513 — array subtype allowlist bypass: an array-typed property bypasses the
# same subtype allowlist check. Same root cause (deserialization allowlist evasion).
#
# NOT REACHABLE here: both require the application to deserialize UNTRUSTED JSON into a
# vulnerable type with polymorphic / default typing enabled. Neo4j Community here is bound
# to 127.0.0.1, single trusted user, non-root, and the Story Forge backend is its only
# client — no untrusted JSON is fed to Neo4j's bundled Jackson, and the Bolt protocol (not
# JSON) carries queries. There is no attacker-controlled deserialization path.
# Bundled by Neo4j like the netty/shiro jars above — no image bump fixes it until a Neo4j
# 5.26.x patch reships jackson-databind >= 2.21.4.
# Drop when: a soaked (>= 7-day) Neo4j 5.26.x patch bundles jackson-databind >= 2.21.4
# (re-scan to confirm both CVEs are gone); checked at each neo4j tag bump.
CVE-2026-54512
CVE-2026-54513
